      <h3>THE FINANCIAL STATE OF CANADA POST</h3>
   
      <p>
        Canada Post has, for the last 17 years, been seeing a decline in their
        profits as letter delivery becomes increasingly replaced by the
        internet, while faster, cheaper competitors such as UPS and FedEx have
        been growing their shares in the parcel delivery market.
        <br /><br />
        On the other hand, they are in a unique position as a federal Crown corporation
        to deliver services to all communities across Canada. As underpinned in initiatives
        such as their introduction of ‚Äòcommunity hub‚Äô-style post offices, they are
        increasing efforts in serving rural areas as part of their solution outside
        of their existing services in order to establish financial self-sustainability.
      </p>
 

      <h3>THE POTENTIAL OF POSTAL WORKERS IN SENIOR CARE</h3>

      <div style="background-color: #FAFAFA; border: 1px dashed #333;">
        <p>
          "The definition of ‚Äúpostal work‚Äù has been expanding. In some places,
          French postal workers now pick up prescriptions, return library books,
          and deliver flowers. Last year, only twenty eight per cent of La
          Poste‚Äôs revenue came from sending mail."
        </p>
        <p>
          - In France, Elder Care Comes with the Mail, ¬†Zoey Poll, The New
          Yorker
        </p>
      </div>
      <p>
        Across the globe, successful examples of senior check-in services
        delivered by postal workers, including the ‚ÄúMimamori‚Äù program from Japan
        Post and the ‚ÄúVeiller sur mes parents‚Äù program from the French La Poste,
        already exist.
        <br /><br />
        Additionally, since 2016, the Canadian Union of Postal Workers has been advocating
        for Canada Post to leverage its unique positioning and network of over (12540
        + 28,400) letter carriers to establish a check-in service for seniors.
        <br /><br />
        Furthermore, the National Institute on Ageing (NIA), a research centre based
        at Toronto Metropolitan University, also advocates that Canada Post is in
        a unique position to deliver such a service. Citing a poll conducted by Leger
        conducted in 2015, they state that letter carriers are amongst the most trusted
        professions in Canada, with 87% of Canadians saying they trusted their mail
        carriers.
        <br /><br />Although the proposal was modelled from overseas solutions,
        there was definitely opportunity within Canada‚Äôs seniors as well, with
        Statistics Canada reporting that 1 in 4 Canadians will be over the age
        of 65 by 2030 (in comparison to 15.3% in 2013), and the NIA and Canadian
        Medical Association reporting that 96% of Canadians want to age at home
        for as long as possible.
      </p>
    </div>
